Q2:Can we predict a country’s status based on its life expectancy?

LED.DATA$Developed = ifelse(LED.DATA$Status == 'Developed', 1, 0)

sinQmod = glm(Developed~Lifeexpectancy, family=binomial, data=LED.DATA)
summary(sinQmod)

Creating a binomial response variable for a countries status.

pred = predict(sinQmod, newdata = LED.DATA, type = "response")
pred = ifelse(pred > 0.5, 1, 0)
accuracy = (length(LED.DATA$Developed) - sum(abs(pred-LED.DATA$Developed), na.rm = TRUE)) / length(LED.DATA$Developed)
accuracy
## [1] 0.8818924

We looked at the prediction accuracy of our model and found that it predicted accurately 88% of the time.

B0 = summary(sinQmod)$coef[1]

B1 = summary(sinQmod)$coef[2]

plot(Developed~Lifeexpectancy, ylim=c(-0.3,1.3), xlim=c(40, 110), data=LED.DATA)

curve(exp(B0+B1*x)/(1+exp(B0+B1*x)),add=TRUE, col="red")

Q1: What is the best classification model for developed vs developing countries using all of the quantitative variables in the data set?

led = read.csv("led.csv")
set.seed(346)
led$SPLIT = sample(x = c("Train","Test"), size = 2938, replace = T, prob = c(0.85,0.15))

ledC = na.omit(led)
drop.cols = c('SPLIT', 'Country', 'Year')
TrainC = ledC %>% filter(SPLIT == "Train") %>% dplyr::select(-c(SPLIT, Country, Year))
TestC = ledC %>% filter(SPLIT == "Test") %>% dplyr::select(-c(SPLIT, Country, Year))
X_TrainC = TrainC %>% dplyr::select(-Status)
Y_TrainC = TrainC%>% dplyr::select(Status)
X_TestC = TestC %>% dplyr::select(-Status)
Y_TestC = TestC %>% dplyr::select(Status)
lda.fit = lda(Status~., data = TrainC )
plot(lda.fit)

lda.pred = predict(lda.fit, TestC)
lda.class = lda.pred$class
Y_TestC1 = Y_TestC[,1]
table(lda.class, Y_TestC1)
##             Y_TestC1
## lda.class    Developed Developing
##   Developed         21          6
##   Developing        11        184
LDA_Accuracy = mean(lda.class == Y_TestC[,1])

K-Nearest Neighbor

X_TrainC1 = as.data.frame(X_TrainC) 
Y_TrainC1 = Y_TrainC[,1]
knn.pred = knn(X_TrainC1, X_TestC, Y_TrainC1, k= 1)
Y_TestC1 = Y_TestC[,1]
table(knn.pred, Y_TestC1)
##             Y_TestC1
## knn.pred     Developed Developing
##   Developed         12         15
##   Developing        20        175
KNN_Accuracy = mean(knn.pred == Y_TestC1)

As K increases, observations increasingly become classified as developing.

knn.2 = knn(X_TrainC1, X_TestC, Y_TrainC1, k= 2)
knn.38 = knn(X_TrainC1, X_TestC, Y_TrainC1, k= 38)
table(knn.2, Y_TestC1)
##             Y_TestC1
## knn.2        Developed Developing
##   Developed         11         14
##   Developing        21        176
table(knn.38, Y_TestC1)
##             Y_TestC1
## knn.38       Developed Developing
##   Developed          0          0
##   Developing        32        190

Support Vector Machine

classifier = svm(formula = Status~., data = TrainC, type = 'C-classification', kernel = 'linear')
y_pred = predict(classifier, newdata = TestC)
table(Y_TestC[,1], y_pred)
##             y_pred
##              Developed Developing
##   Developed         23          9
##   Developing         6        184
SVM_Accuracy = mean(Y_TestC[,1] == y_pred)
Accuracy= data.frame(LDA= LDA_Accuracy, KNN = KNN_Accuracy, SVM = SVM_Accuracy)
head(Accuracy)
##         LDA       KNN       SVM
## 1 0.9234234 0.8423423 0.9324324

SVM has the highest accuracy rate with 0.9324324.

Q2: What is the best model for life expectancy using other quantitative variables?

Ridge Regression

x <- model.matrix(Lifeexpectancy~.,data=led1)[,-1]
y <- led1$Lifeexpectancy
grid.lambda = 10^seq(10, -2, length = 100)
ridge.model = glmnet(x, y, alpha = 0, lambda = grid.lambda)
x1 <- model.matrix(Lifeexpectancy~.,data=Train3)[,-1]
y1 <- Train3$Lifeexpectancy
ridge.model.train = glmnet(x1, y1, alpha = 0, lambda = grid.lambda)
cv.out3 = cv.glmnet(x1, y1, alpha = 0)
best.lambda = cv.out3$lambda.min
ridge.pred <-predict(ridge.model.train, s = best.lambda, newx = X_test2)
mspe.ridge <-mean((ridge.pred-Y_test2)^2)

final.model <-glmnet(x, y, alpha = 0, lambda = best.lambda)
Coef.Ridge <-coef(final.model)[1:19, ]

Lasso

lasso.model.train <-glmnet(x, y, alpha = 1, lambda = grid.lambda)
cv.out4 <-cv.glmnet(X_train2, Y_train2, alpha = 1)
best.lambda1 <- cv.out4$lambda.min

Q1: How has mean life expectancy changed over the past 15 years for developing vs developed countries?

q1.data <- LED.DATA %>% 
  filter(is.na(Lifeexpectancy) == FALSE) %>% #na value was causing part of graph to not show up 
  group_by(Status, Year) %>% 
  summarize( 
    mean = mean(Lifeexpectancy)
  )

print(q1.data)
## # A tibble: 32 x 3
## # Groups:   Status [2]
##    Status     Year  mean

ggplot(q1.data, aes(Year, mean, color = Status)) + geom_point() + geom_line() + labs(y = "Mean Life Expectancy")

Q2: Has the mean life expectancy for each continent changed significantly over time?

web.table = xml2::read_html("http://www.geonames.org/countries/")
Continent.DATA = web.table %>%
  html_table(fill = T) %>%
  .[[2]] %>% 
 dplyr::select(Country, Continent) %>% 
  mutate(Country = ifelse(Country == "DR Congo", "Congo, Democratic Republic of", Country), )

q2.data <- left_join(LED.DATA, Continent.DATA, by = "Country") %>% 
filter(is.na(Lifeexpectancy) == FALSE) %>% #graph gets gaps in it without this line
  mutate(Continent = ifelse(is.na(Continent)==TRUE, "North America", Continent),
        Continent = ifelse(Continent == "AF", "Africa", Continent),
        Continent = ifelse(Continent == "AS", "Asia", Continent),
        Continent = ifelse(Continent == "EU", "Europe", Continent),
         Continent = ifelse(Continent == "OC", "Oceania", Continent),
         Continent = ifelse(Continent == "AF", "Africa", Continent),
         Continent = ifelse(Continent == "SA", "South America", Continent)
         ) %>%
  group_by(Continent, Year) %>%
  summarize(
    mean = mean(Lifeexpectancy)
    )

ggplot(q2.data, aes(Year, mean, color = Continent)) + geom_point() + geom_line()

URL.DATA = "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_countries_by_life_expectancy"
Gender.DATA2 = URL.DATA %>%
  xml2::read_html() %>%
  html_table(fill = T) %>%
  .[[1]]
Gender.DATA <- Gender.DATA2 %>%
  rename("Both Lifeexpectancy" = "Both sexes lifeexpectancy", "Country" = "Country and regions", "FemLifeExpect"= "Female life expectancy", "MaleLifeExpect" = "Male life expectancy") %>%
 dplyr::select("Country", "FemLifeExpect", "MaleLifeExpect")

followq2.data <- inner_join(LED.DATA, Gender.DATA, by = "Country") %>% 
  dplyr::select("Country", "Year", "Status", "Lifeexpectancy", "FemLifeExpect", "MaleLifeExpect") %>% 
  filter(Year == 2015) %>% #because the data for the gender is for 2015
  group_by(Status)

ggplot(followq2.data, aes(FemLifeExpect, MaleLifeExpect, color = Status)) + geom_jitter() + geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1) + labs(x = "Female Life Expectancy", y = "Male Life Expectancy")

We noticed that GDP was the most correlated factor with life expectancy, which was suprising to us, as we expected disease, or infant death rates to have more correlation. Because of this relationship with GDP and life expectancy, we decided to make one our our follow up questions explore that relationship further. For predicting life expectancy, we noticed the Lasso model was the best. For the k-nearest neighbors classification model, we noticed that as k increased, more countries are classified as developing. For the first question, we looked into how accurate our model was when it came to predicting life expectancy. As for question two, we wanted to look into the differences between male and female life expectancies.
